<br>
This stunt has really gotten under my skin.  I just wonder if I'm the only one who feels that way about it.<br>
<br>
I'm not hardly as mad at the woman for pulling it as I am at IGFA for coddling her with it.  IMO, the decision on this should have been swift and final.  &quot;No mam.  You may have very well caught the world record, but you have failed to bring it to the weigh in, therefore, you petition for acceptance has been denied.&quot; <br>
<br>
Over the years fishing tournaments, I've seen some incredibly stupid things happen.  Specifically, I've seen people release their fish before the weigh in because the assumed they didn't have enough to be in the money and didn't want to fool with weighing in a loosing string.  Later they found out, the 2 pounds of fish they had would have actually gotten them a check.  In that case, I don't care if they were weighed on 50 scales in the boat and 60 people saw them do it, they still don't count because they didn't follow the procedure of bringing them to the official scales and having the weighmaster of the tournament inspect and verify the fish.  <br>
<br>
In this case, I don't think its unreasonable to expect that a world record bass has been inspected by A Game Warden, A Biologist, A tournement official or some other person knowledgable of the fish.  A son and a bystander just doesn't cut the mustard in my mind.  <br>
<br>
The more I hear, see and read, the more this sounds like a &quot;Fish Tale&quot; and not based in truth.  I'm sure IGFA is afraid of lawsuits or discrimination or something else they'd have put their foot down, but they are they record keeping body just like the official NFL Stat Keeper.  Rules are Rules and they should be followed.  I'm sure that the Perry fish didn't get near the scrutiny I'm expecting in this case, but then again, his fish was supper, that was 1930 some odd, and times were quite different.  I'd venture to say that baseball records from the 30's aren't as accurate or as complete as they are today either.  The thing is, that fish when caught today is worth well over 5 million bucks.  It not just a case of Lucky 13's anymore.  Its big business, and people are looking to win that lottery.  I figure if this is allowed, more like it will be allowed and 10 years from now, the world record largemouth will be no bigger of a deal than someone setting a track record at the Pomona Drag Strip.<br>
