<br>
“Dzialo said the bass was identified by a state Fish and Game representative and was weighed on a certified scale before Trew released it.”<br>
<br>
That gives me the impression that the rep was present when the fish was caught. I think it even implies he was there when the fish was weighed and released. Dzialo is the Executive Director of the National Fresh Water Fishing Hall of Fame, which also recognizes this fish as an unofficial world record. I think they require an autopsy for a record to be official. What a joke. I already emailed the writer of the article and am waiting for a reply. Statements like that lend further credibility to this fairy tale. The truth is the G&amp;F rep identified that the fish in the picture we have all seen is a bass. Whoopee!<br>
<br>
Here is another statement:<br>
<br>
&quot;Their excitement mounted as Leaha Trew struggled to pull the bass aboard the boat, and they used the last frame on their last roll of film to snap its picture -- and then released it.&quot;<br>
<br>
